==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bak(k)a-'', from Indo-European ''*bhōg-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[bakkan]] (Dutch [[bakken]]), Old High German [[backan]] (German [[backen]]), Old Norse [[baka]] (Norwegian [[baka]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[φώγειν]]

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'bakan/

===Verb===
'''bacan''' (class II strong)
# to [[bake]]
#:''Fif bacaþ on anum ofene'': five are baking in one oven.  (''Leviticus'')

===Declension===
====Present Tense====

*Singular: ic bace, þu bæcst, hé bæcþ
*Plural: wé, gé, híe bacaþ
*Subjunctive: bace ''sg'', bacen ''pl''
*Imperative: bac! ''sg'', bacaþ! ''pl''
*Participle: bacende

====Past Tense====

*Singular: ic bóc, þu bóce, hé bóc
*Plural: wé, gé, híe bócon
*Subjunctive: bóce ''sg'', bōcen ''pl''
*Participle: (ġe)bacen, (ġe)bæcen

====Inflected Infinitive====
*tó bacenne

